<font color="#FF0000">I REMEMBER</font><br>
<tt>Fri Jan  3  9:15:38 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
My experience was different from most as are my memories.  As a professional soldier--read lifer--going and fighting was part of what I signed on for, so I can't look back and complan how it changed my life.  It didn't.  As an Advisor,it did give me an opportunity to live and fight with the South Vietnamese and I came to admire the private soldeir very much. I also got a first hand view of what the often denied VC policy of terror ment to the indavidual Vietnamese. Picking up the body of a three year old girl who'd been executed because she was the daughter of a ARVN Lieutentan, sticks in my mind.<br>
   As a professional, two things do stick in my mind: <br>
   1. The contempt we received from our &quot;privledged class.&quot;  Along with that was the added little goodies: while in Viet Nam, by wife would receive phone calls, telling her I was dead, and others telling her they hoped I would be killed or crippled.  Nice people.  <br>
         I remember. <br>
   2. our abandonment of the South while the North crossed the DMZ in force. We wouldn't even send them ammo.  Shameful affair.  My counterpart spent 16 years in a &quot;re-eduction&quot; camp, where 80% were starved and/or worked to death.<br>
         I remember.<br>
I wrote a littl ditty:<br>
                 Recent History<br>
       A study of recent history,<br>
            And events that have come to pass,<br>
       Shows that an allie who plays ball with the US<br>
           Ends up with the bat up his  axx.
